<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-07-25T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-07-25T15:00:00-05:00" n="565" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d565">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M)/7639.: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-07-25T16:00:00-04:00">July 25,
                                1942—4 p.m.</date>
                        </dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>669. Your no. 864 of July 22, 10 a.m. Our basic interest in the mercury at
                        Kunming is a preclusive one. It is important that it does not fall into
                        Japanese hands. If the Russians acquire these stocks, please suggest that
                        they be transported by northwest route at early date. Keep the Department
                        informed.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>